templateAssets.content:
UCLA's life science majors require the completion of extensive preparatory coursework prior to transfer, therefore, you must be admitted directly into a life science major; you will not be able to change from a non-life science major into a life science major after admission to UCLA.


Students who have placed out of UCLA's Math 31A course based on AP/IB credit may be required to complete UCLA's Math 3C, 32A or an equivalent course after transfer.


The community college statistics course included on this agreement has been approved as a substitute for Statistics 13, however, it may not transfer as an exact UCLA equivalent.


UCLA's Chem 153A is an upper-division course that satisfies a major requirement but is NOT required for admission. After transferring, students must petition for transfer credit and should contact the academic advisor for their major for additional support and details about this process.

The Molecular, Cell, and Developmental Biology major provides undergraduate students with cutting-edge information on the molecular process involved in cell function and differentiation. The curriculum consists of several core and elective disciplines that are updated yearly to reflect advances in the field. 


Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major as well as important details to review. THIS MAJOR IS HIGHLY SELECTIVE.


To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer:

  • One year of Biology for major with Laboratory,
  • One year of General Chemistry with Laboratory,
  • One year of Calculus, and
  • One semester of Organic Chemistry with Lab.

Completion of a second semester of Organic Chemistry or one year of Calculus Based Physics is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED. (If your college does not offer a two semester or three quarter sequence in calculus based physics, it is recommended that you complete Physics 5ABC at UCLA after transfer).

All courses must be taken for a letter grade.


For more information about this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://mcdb.ucla.edu and https://admission.ucla.edu.


PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirements for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed below.

The AP Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus AB exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
  • A score of 4 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A and 31B.


The IB Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 6 or higher on the IB HL Math Analysis & Approaches exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
